# node-worker #

Base for NodeJS Gearman workers for SSP.

## Usage ##

Create a worker object:

    const Worker = require( '@ssp/worker' );
    const worker = new Worker( {} );

Register some tasks:

    worker.registerTask( 'my-worker.do-something-awesome', function( data ) {
      // data is an object containing whatever parameters were passed to
      // the method call
    }, options );

Note that you can't use a fat arrow function when defining a task, as it has
`this` set to a context object that you would lose access to if you did that.
If using `function(){}` really bothers you, you can register multiple tasks
at once, like this:

    worker.registerTasks( {
      'my-worker.task-1'( data ) { },
      'my-worker.task-2'( data ) { },
      'my-worker.task-3'( data ) { },
    }, options );

## Tasks, Data, and Context ##

Worker tasks get the data passed in the call as an argument.  A task
can either return the data it wants sent back directly, or can return
a promise for that data.

When the task function is called, `this` will be bound to a context object
that includes these methods and properties:

  * status( msg ) - Send a status report back to the client
  * workdata( data ) - Send work data back to the client
  * warn( msg ) - Send a warning message to the client
  * error( msg ) - Send an error message to the client
  * data - A reference to the data that is passed in as the argument
  * secret - Secret information (if requested by the worker)

## Secrets ##

If the worker needs secret information (API keys, passwords, etc),
these should not be stored in the repo, they should be stored securely
in Vault and accessed using the SSP `node-secrets` module.  Rather than
setting up `node-secrets` yourself, the worker can do it for you, all you
have to do is pass the storage location for where your secrets can be found.

    const worker = new Worker( { secret : 'secret/ssp/worker/my-worker' } );

Then, when your task method is called, the secret information will be
available in `this.secret`:

    worker.registerTask( 'check-secrets', function( data ) {
      console.log( this.secret );
    } );

